{
  "sectionCode": "10/22",
  "sectionCodeDisplay": "10/22",
  "title": "Branches of Mathematics",
  "outline": [
    {
      "level": "A",
      "levelType": "major",
      "text": "Set theory",
      "children": [
        {
          "level": "1",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "Origins of set theory and the definitions of a set and a set element, or member",
          "children": []
        },
        {
          "level": "2",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "Introduction to set theory",
          "children": [
            {
              "level": "a",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Fundamental set concepts",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "b",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Essential features of Cantorian set theory",
              "children": []
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "level": "3",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "Axiomatic set theory: formal analyses of set theory based upon certain fundamental assumptions or undefined notions called axioms [see also 10/21. B.3. a.]",
          "children": [
            {
              "level": "a",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Postulates of axiomatic set theory: the Zermelo-Fraenkel axioms, the von Neumann- Bernays-Godel axioms",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "b",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Limitations of axiomatic set theory: failure of attempts to prove the consistency of axiomatic set theory, Godel's theorem",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "c",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "The present status of axiomatic set theory: profound changes in axiomatic set theory as a result of recent discoveries",
              "children": []
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "level": "B",
      "levelType": "major",
      "text": "Algebra",
      "children": [
        {
          "level": "1",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "Arithmetic",
          "children": [
            {
              "level": "a",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Fundamental definitions and laws: the concepts of natural number and integer; the binary operations of addition and multiplication; the commutative and associative laws of addition; the commutative, associative, and distributive laws of multiplication",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "b",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Theory of divisors: extension of natural number concepts to non-integers, fractions resulting from the binary operation of division",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "c",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Number systems and notation: use of the positional principle and the symbol zero to specify , magnitude in sequences of digits; number systems having different bases --e.g., binary, decimal, and sexagesimal systems [see also 10/23.A. 1.)",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "d",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Arithmetic calculation with decimals: binary operations with decimals; divisibility rules; calculation of square, cube, and higher roots",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "e",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Logarithms: formal definition of logarithms, use of logarithms to reduce the operations of multiplication and division to the simpler operations of addition and subtraction [see also 10/23.A.4.b.]",
              "children": []
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "level": "2",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "Elementary and multivariate algebra",
          "children": [
            {
              "level": "a",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Algebra as an extension and generalization of arithmetic",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "b",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Basic algebraic properties of numbers",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "c",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Polynomials and rational functions",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "d",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Solution of equations: the principal problem of elementary algebra",
              "children": []
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "level": "3",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "Linear and multilinear algebra",
          "children": [
            {
              "level": "a",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Linear algebra",
